 of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Holland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, German, Dutch, Danish, Norwegian, Swedish, French, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from <i>Holland</i>, a province of the Netherlands.","English: habitational name from Downholland or Upholland (Lancashire), Hulland (Derbyshire), the Parts of Holland, one of the three administrative subdivisions of Lincolnshire, any of the four places called Hoyland (southern Yorkshire), and possibly Great and Little Holland (Essex). The placenames all derive from Old English <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’.","English: habitational name either from Hoeland (Farm) in Bury (Sussex), or from Holland's Barn in Albourne (Sussex). The placename in Bury has the same etymology as in 1 above, while the placename in Albourne may derive from Old English <i>hol</i> ‘hole, hollow’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."],"variants":[{"name":"Hollands","meanings":["English: variant of   Holland  , especially 3, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Dutch: genitivized form of   Holland  ."]},{"name":"Howland","meanings":["English: variant of   Holland  .","Americanized form of Norwegian   Hovland  .","History: Howland was the name of three Quaker brothers, original settlers in Marshfield, MA. They were from Huntingdonshire, England. The eldest, John Howland (<i>c.</i> 1593–1672) was a passenger on the <i>Mayflower</i>, servant to Gov. John Carver, who died in the first winter at Plymouth Colony."]},{"name":"Hollander","meanings":["Dutch (also <b>Den Hollander</b>), German (also <b>Holländer</b>), English, Swedish, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Holland (see   Holland   1)."]},{"name":"Holand","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Holland  .","Norwegian: habitational name from about twenty farmsteads so named, composed of Old Norse <i>hár</i> ‘high’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, field’, denoting a high-lying farm."]},{"name":"Aland","meanings":["Scandinavian (<b>Åland</b>): topographic name from the Åland Islands in the Gulf of Bothnia.","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>atte lande</i> (Old French <i>laund</i>) ‘dweller at the glade or pasture’, or sometimes perhaps, ‘dweller at the old cultivated land(s)’ from Old English <i>eald</i>, <i>ald</i> ‘old’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."]},{"name":"Hollon","meanings":["English: altered form of   Holland  ."]}]},{"name":"Ulf","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and Swedish: from Old Norse <i>Úlfr</i> ‘wolf’.  See  <b>Wolf</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Uffe","meanings":["variant of   Ulf ."]},{"name":"Ulv","meanings":["spelling of   Ulf ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ulf De Holland was born in 1118, in Up Holland, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Raufe De Longworth, was 49 and his mother, Agnes de Arderne, was 38. He had at least 1 son with Eva de Kellett. He died in Somme, Picardie, France."},"et":{"1118–":"1118–Surnud","1098–1160":"1098–1160","1118–Male":"1118–Surnud","1120–1200":"1120–1200","1146–1204":"1146–1204","1070–1140":"1070–1140","1080–1118":"1080–1118","1118":"1118","1080":"1080","1204":"1204","1146":"1146","1200":"1200","1120":"1120","1098":"1098","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","1070":"1070","Upholland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1118–":"1118–Kuollut","1098–1160":"1098–1160","1118–Male":"1118–Kuollut","1120–1200":"1120–1200","1146–1204":"1146–1204","1070–1140":"1070–1140","1080–1118":"1080–1118","1118":"1118","1080":"1080","1204":"1204","1146":"1146","1200":"1200","1120":"1120","1098":"1098","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","1070":"1070","Upholland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Ranska"},"fr":{"1118–":"1118–Décédé","1098–1160":"1098–116